default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default“Systems that show high performance and an equitable distribution of learning
default outcomes tend to be comprehensive, requiring teachers and schools to embrace diverse student populations through personalised educational pathways.  In contrast, school systems that assume that students have different destinations with different expectati
defaultons and differentiation in terms of how they are placed in schools, classes, and grades often show less equitable outcomes without overall performance advantage.” (pg13)
